I'm not saying that coal plants are not responsible, just that the data in this report doesn't immediately support that conclusion. Coal plants release other chemicals as part of combustion, & so should show up in flask samples and/or water in surrounding areas, if not scrubbed.

If you are looking for answers about sulfates, I'd start with soil composition, and have a closer look at any rainfall and wind pattern changes that occurred after the wildfires. Mollisol: https:// en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mollisol pic.twitter.com/z6FwRzYiIJ

There is a lot of data, but from 2016 & that coincides with wildfires. Also, only larger particulates are shown (< 10 µm), more consistent with forest fires than coal plants. Thousands of firefighters deployed as wildfires rage in France, Portugal, Spain https://www. cnn.com/2016/08/11/eur ope/europe-france-spain-portugal-wildfires/index.html …
I found your data on the website for the video. I'm looking at this now, and for anyone else who might have missed it, I found it at https:// beyond-coal.eu/data/

I'm not saying this is wrong, I'm saying I'm not convinced because there's no specific detail to point to a particular plant as causative. You need more detail, such as air and water samples across the region over time, & preferably weather data showing wind patterns.
